    <exercise label="question2_14_3">
    <statement>
      <p>Which of the following statements are equivalent?</p>
    </statement>
    <choices>
      <choice correct="yes">
        <statement>
          <p>x = x + y</p>
        </statement>
        <feedback>
          <p>x is updated to be the old value of x plus the value of y.</p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice>
        <statement>
          <p>y += x</p>
        </statement>
        <feedback>
          <p>y is updated to be the old value of y plus the value of x.</p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice>
        <statement>
          <p>x += x + y</p>
        </statement>
        <feedback>
          <p>This updates x to be its old value (because of the +=) plus its old value again
            (because of the x on the right side) plus the value of y, so it's equivalent to x = x +
            x + y</p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice correct="yes">
        <statement>
          <p>x += y</p>
        </statement>
        <feedback>
          <p>x is updated to be the old value of x plus the value of y.</p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice>
        <statement>
          <p>x++ y</p>
        </statement>
        <feedback>
          <p>++ is not a syntax that means anything in Python.</p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
    </choices>
  </exercise>
